"algs.info.zbll.title" = "About ZBLL";
"algs.info.zbll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of ZBLL";
"algs.info.zbll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.zbll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.zbll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.zbll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.zbll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.zbll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.zbll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.zbll.overview.p1" = "**ZBLL**, short for **Zborowski-Bruchem Last Layer**, is an advanced algorithm set used to solve **the entire last layer in one move** when **all top-layer edges are already oriented**. It combines recognition and permutation into a single step, often producing very efficient last-layer solutions.";
"algs.info.zbll.history.p1" = "ZBLL was developed in the early 2000s as part of the ZB method by **Zbigniew Zborowski** and **Ron van Bruchem**. Although related one-look last-layer ideas existed earlier, the speedcubing community eventually adopted the name **“ZBLL”** for this family of algorithms.";
"algs.info.zbll.size.b1" = "**472 algorithms** in total";
"algs.info.zbll.size.b2" = "Average move count is around **12 HTM**";
"algs.info.zbll.size.b3" = "Most effective when **all last-layer edges are already oriented**";
"algs.info.zbll.size.b4" = "Especially useful in methods like **ZZ**, where edge orientation is preserved after F2L";
"algs.info.zbll.insights.p1" = "Because ZBLL is such a large set, most cubers learn it gradually rather than all at once. In practice, many solvers begin with the **subsets** that give the clearest efficiency gains in real solves. Some groups, such as **S** and **AS** cases, are often learned later or skipped entirely, since their alternatives are already relatively simple.";
"algs.info.zbll.insights.p2" = "ZBLL is commonly organized by the underlying **COLL case**: **T, U, L, Pi, Sune, Anti-Sune, and H**. Some systems also mention an additional **“PLL” or “O” group**, although this group is not always counted separately in practice, and some collections, including this one, do not treat it as its own set.";
"algs.info.zbll.insights.p3" = "These sets are then divided further into **subsets**. In the full classification, each subset contains **12 cases**, corresponding to the different **edge cycles** that can occur while the COLL case remains the same.";
"algs.info.zbll.recognition.p1" = "ZBLL cases are recognized by identifying both the underlying **COLL case** and the corresponding **edge cycle**. The corner pattern determines the main family, while the edge permutation determines the exact case within that family.";
"algs.info.zbll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for cubers who already know **full PLL and OLL** and want more advanced one-look last-layer solutions. It is especially suitable for **ZZ** solvers, but can also be valuable for **CFOP** users who want to reduce last-layer step count and explore more efficient finishes.";
"algs.info.zbll.quote.p1" = "“Most cubers do not learn ZBLL all at once. They build it **subset by subset**, starting with the cases that offer the clearest **practical value**.”";
"algs.info.pll.title" = "About PLL";
"algs.info.pll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of PLL";
"algs.info.pll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.pll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.pll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.pll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.pll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.pll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.pll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.pll.overview.p1" = "**PLL**, short for **Permutation of the Last Layer**, is the final step of the standard two-look last-layer structure in CFOP. After the last-layer pieces are oriented, PLL solves their remaining permutation in **one algorithm**, finishing the cube.";
"algs.info.pll.history.p1" = "PLL took shape inside the early **Fridrich method** in the 1980s and is usually associated with work by **Hans Dockhorn**, **Anneke Treep**, and later **Jessica Fridrich**. As CFOP spread through speedcubing, PLL became the standard last step for many solvers.";
"algs.info.pll.size.b1" = "**21 algorithms** in the full set";
"algs.info.pll.size.b2" = "Often described as **13 core cases** if mirrors and inverses are grouped together";
"algs.info.pll.size.b3" = "Average optimal length is roughly **11 to 12 HTM**";
"algs.info.pll.size.b4" = "Used after **OLL** or any other step that leaves the last layer oriented";
"algs.info.pll.insights.p1" = "PLL is one of the highest-value algorithm sets in speedcubing because learning the full set immediately removes the need for a second permutation step. For many cubers, it is the first large set learned after beginner methods.";
"algs.info.pll.insights.p2" = "The set is often grouped into broad families such as **edge-only cases**, **corner-only cases**, and mixed permutations. Common names like **T**, **J**, **R**, **G**, and **N** are now deeply embedded in cubing culture.";
"algs.info.pll.insights.p3" = "In practice, PLL rewards confident recognition more than raw algorithm count. Clean recognition from **headlights**, **bars**, and side blocks often saves more time than shaving one move off an algorithm.";
"algs.info.pll.recognition.p1" = "PLL is recognized by looking at how the already oriented last-layer pieces are permuted. Solvers typically use features such as **headlights**, solved bars, adjacent blocks, and overall edge cycle patterns to identify the case.";
"algs.info.pll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for any cuber moving beyond beginner last-layer methods. Full PLL is one of the most practical investments in CFOP and also serves as a foundation for more advanced sets like **COLL**, **OLLCP**, and **ZBLL**.";
"algs.info.pll.quote.p1" = "“Full PLL is often the first moment when a solver feels the last layer become truly fast, because the cube can now finish in **one clean permutation step**.”";
"algs.info.oll.title" = "About OLL";
"algs.info.oll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of OLL";
"algs.info.oll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.oll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.oll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.oll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.oll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.oll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.oll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.oll.overview.p1" = "**OLL**, short for **Orientation of the Last Layer**, solves the orientation of all last-layer pieces in one step while ignoring their permutation. In CFOP, it is normally used after F2L and before PLL.";
"algs.info.oll.history.p1" = "Like PLL, OLL grew out of the early **Fridrich method** in the 1980s. The modern full set was refined over time as speedcubers collected and optimized algorithms for every orientation state of the last layer.";
"algs.info.oll.size.b1" = "**57 algorithms** in the full set";
"algs.info.oll.size.b2" = "A common milestone is **2-look OLL**, which reduces the learning load at first";
"algs.info.oll.size.b3" = "Average move count is usually around **9 to 10 HTM**";
"algs.info.oll.size.b4" = "Used to convert the last layer into a state that can be finished with **PLL**";
"algs.info.oll.insights.p1" = "OLL is one of the biggest jumps in CFOP because it turns the last layer from a multi-step process into a clean orientation step followed by PLL. That is why many cubers learn it gradually after mastering full PLL.";
"algs.info.oll.insights.p2" = "The set is commonly learned by broad shape families such as **dot**, **line**, **cross**, and **corner orientation patterns**. This lets solvers build recognition in layers rather than memorizing 57 isolated cases.";
"algs.info.oll.insights.p3" = "Even among advanced solvers, not all OLL cases feel equal. Some are extremely ergonomic and fast, while others are remembered more by recognition cues and setup habits than by raw move count.";
"algs.info.oll.recognition.p1" = "OLL is recognized by the orientation pattern of the last layer: the shape formed by oriented edges, plus the orientation of visible top-layer corners. Efficient recognition usually combines top-face shape with side stickers.";
"algs.info.oll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for cubers who already know **full PLL** and want a complete two-step last layer. Full OLL is a major practical upgrade for CFOP and a prerequisite for understanding more advanced last-layer systems.";
"algs.info.oll.quote.p1" = "“Learning OLL is less about memorizing 57 random pictures and more about building confidence with a handful of **recognition families** that repeat across the whole set.”";
"algs.info.f2l.title" = "About F2L";
"algs.info.f2l.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of F2L";
"algs.info.f2l.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.f2l.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.f2l.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.f2l.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.f2l.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.f2l.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.f2l.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.f2l.overview.p1" = "**F2L**, short for **First Two Layers**, solves a corner-edge pair and inserts it into its slot at the same time. In modern CFOP, it replaces the older beginner approach of solving the second layer separately and is the core of fast solving before the last layer.";
"algs.info.f2l.history.p1" = "The corner-edge pairing idea appeared in the late 1970s, notably in work associated with **John Conway**, **David Singmaster's circle**, and later methods that predated modern speedcubing notation. It became central to the **Fridrich method**, where intuitive F2L eventually replaced more rigid step-by-step layer building.";
"algs.info.f2l.size.b1" = "There is **no single fixed full set**, because much of F2L is solved intuitively";
"algs.info.f2l.size.b2" = "A commonly studied subset is the **41 last-slot cases**";
"algs.info.f2l.size.b3" = "Strong F2L usually saves more time through **lookahead** than through raw algorithm count";
"algs.info.f2l.size.b4" = "Advanced last-slot branches such as **WV**, **VLS**, and **ZBLS** all grow out of F2L structure";
"algs.info.f2l.insights.p1" = "F2L is where a large part of real solve speed comes from. Better pair building, better slot choice, and smoother lookahead often matter more here than shaving a move off the last layer.";
"algs.info.f2l.insights.p2" = "Most cubers begin with intuitive F2L, then learn selected algorithms for awkward cases. This is why F2L sits in an unusual place between pure intuition and formal algorithm study.";
"algs.info.f2l.insights.p3" = "Once a solver becomes comfortable with F2L structure, many advanced systems start to make sense: last-slot tricks, edge-orientation-aware inserts, and one-look transitions all build on the same basic pair logic.";
"algs.info.f2l.recognition.p1" = "F2L recognition means tracking a target corner, its matching edge, and their relation to the open slots. Efficient solvers identify both the pair state and the best insertion path before finishing the previous pair.";
"algs.info.f2l.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for every cuber moving beyond beginner layer-by-layer methods. Strong F2L is foundational not only for **CFOP**, but also for understanding many advanced subset systems built on the last slot.";
"algs.info.f2l.quote.p1" = "“Fast F2L is rarely about knowing the most algorithms. It is about seeing pairs early, choosing good slots, and keeping the cube moving with **lookahead**.”";
"algs.info.coll.title" = "About COLL";
"algs.info.coll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of COLL";
"algs.info.coll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.coll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.coll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.coll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.coll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.coll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.coll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.coll.overview.p1" = "**COLL**, short for **Corners of the Last Layer**, solves all last-layer corners in one step while preserving already oriented edges. After a COLL case, the cube is reduced to one of the **EPLL** cases.";
"algs.info.coll.history.p1" = "COLL became popular as a bridge between basic last-layer systems and larger one-look families. It is closely associated with edge-oriented methods such as **ZZ**, but CFOP solvers also adopted it as a practical upgrade over OCLL plus PLL.";
"algs.info.coll.size.b1" = "**42 algorithms** in the full set when mirrors are counted separately";
"algs.info.coll.size.b2" = "Often described as **24 core cases** when mirrors and inverses are grouped";
"algs.info.coll.size.b3" = "Leaves only the **4 EPLL cases** after completion";
"algs.info.coll.size.b4" = "Most useful when last-layer edges are already oriented";
"algs.info.coll.insights.p1" = "COLL is a natural midpoint between OLL/PLL and larger one-look systems. It gives real efficiency gains without the overwhelming size of sets like ZBLL.";
"algs.info.coll.insights.p2" = "Because it solves corners completely, COLL can produce elegant endings and occasionally immediate skips into a solved cube or a very easy EPLL. That makes it especially attractive to solvers who enjoy efficient last-layer finishes.";
"algs.info.coll.insights.p3" = "Many solvers learn COLL by grouping cases with familiar OCLL-style corner patterns. Once those families are stable, the extra corner permutation detail becomes much easier to add.";
"algs.info.coll.recognition.p1" = "COLL is recognized by combining the visible corner orientation pattern with the corner permutation. In practice, many solvers first identify the OCLL-style shape and then confirm which permutation case it is.";
"algs.info.coll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for cubers who already know **full PLL**, are comfortable with **OLL**, and want a manageable path toward more efficient one-look last-layer solving. It is especially attractive for **ZZ** and advanced **CFOP** users.";
"algs.info.coll.quote.p1" = "“COLL often feels like the point where advanced last-layer theory becomes practical: small enough to learn, but strong enough to noticeably change solve endings.”";
"algs.info.ollcp.title" = "About OLLCP";
"algs.info.ollcp.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of OLLCP";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.ollcp.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.ollcp.overview.p1" = "**OLLCP** extends OLL by solving both the **orientation of the last layer** and the **corner permutation** in one step. Like COLL, it leaves an **EPLL** finish, but it starts from the broader family of OLL states instead of only edge-oriented ones.";
"algs.info.ollcp.history.p1" = "OLLCP grew out of speedcubers noticing that many OLL algorithms also control corner permutation. Over time, these cases were cataloged into a larger structured set, with subsets such as **COLL** and **CLL-like edge-oriented families** often treated as especially learnable entry points.";
"algs.info.ollcp.size.b1" = "Commonly counted as **331 algorithms** in total";
"algs.info.ollcp.size.b2" = "Includes **COLL** as one important subset when edges are already oriented";
"algs.info.ollcp.size.b3" = "Leaves only an **EPLL** after the OLLCP step";
"algs.info.ollcp.size.b4" = "Usually learned selectively rather than as a full all-at-once set";
"algs.info.ollcp.insights.p1" = "OLLCP sits in an interesting place: bigger than COLL, but still much smaller than ZBLL. That makes it attractive to solvers who want better last-layer efficiency without committing to the largest one-look families.";
"algs.info.ollcp.insights.p2" = "In practice, many cubers do not aim for full OLLCP at first. They pick subsets with strong ergonomics, useful skips, or familiar recognition and treat the rest as a longer-term project.";
"algs.info.ollcp.insights.p3" = "OLLCP also helps connect different parts of last-layer theory. Once you start thinking about orientation and corner permutation together, sets like COLL, ZBLL, and advanced last-slot systems become easier to relate to each other.";
"algs.info.ollcp.recognition.p1" = "OLLCP is recognized by identifying the **OLL shape** and then determining the **corner permutation** that accompanies it. Compared with plain OLL, the extra recognition burden is the price paid for reducing the final permutation step to EPLL.";
"algs.info.ollcp.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced solvers who already know **full PLL** and a substantial amount of **OLL**, and who want a more realistic stepping stone between standard last-layer solving and very large one-look systems.";
"algs.info.ollcp.quote.p1" = "“OLLCP is appealing because it keeps the familiar OLL framework, but asks a better question: can this same recognition also solve the corners for free?”";
"algs.info.vls.title" = "About VLS";
"algs.info.vls.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of VLS";
"algs.info.vls.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.vls.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.vls.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.vls.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.vls.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.vls.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.vls.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.vls.overview.p1" = "**VLS**, short for **Valk Last Slot**, solves the final F2L pair in a way that also orients the last layer. When it works, it skips plain OLL and flows directly into a PLL or another reduced last-layer finish.";
"algs.info.vls.history.p1" = "The best-known doorway into VLS is **Winter Variation**, published by **Lucas Winter** in 2005. Later work by solvers such as **Mats Valk**, **Rowe Hessler**, and others expanded that idea into the broader VLS family used today.";
"algs.info.vls.size.b1" = "Often counted as **432 algorithms** with mirrors, or **216 core cases** without mirrors";
"algs.info.vls.size.b2" = "Built on the last-slot situation where the target pair is already formed";
"algs.info.vls.size.b3" = "Designed to solve the last slot while also orienting the final layer";
"algs.info.vls.size.b4" = "Commonly learned starting from **Winter Variation**, then expanded subset by subset";
"algs.info.vls.insights.p1" = "VLS is one of the clearest examples of a high-value advanced subset: it attacks the last slot, which is already a major turning point in the solve, and turns it into a bridge toward a shorter last layer.";
"algs.info.vls.insights.p2" = "Most solvers do not approach VLS as one giant set. They begin with the easiest or most frequent-looking subsets, often through Winter Variation, and only later decide whether the larger family is worth deeper study.";
"algs.info.vls.insights.p3" = "Because VLS lives inside last-slot decision making, its practical strength depends heavily on recognition speed. A theoretically powerful case is only useful if the solver can spot it without destroying F2L flow.";
"algs.info.vls.recognition.p1" = "VLS is recognized by looking at the paired last-slot pieces together with the orientation state of the remaining last-layer edges and corners. Efficient recognition depends on seeing both the slot pattern and the last-layer orientation at once.";
"algs.info.vls.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced **CFOP** solvers who already have stable F2L and want to reduce last-layer steps from the last slot. It is especially attractive to cubers who enjoy last-slot subsets such as **WV**, **ZBLS**, and related systems.";
"algs.info.vls.quote.p1" = "“VLS is powerful because it does not ask for a separate last-layer miracle. It asks whether the final pair itself can quietly set up a faster finish.”";
"algs.info.wv.title" = "About WV";
"algs.info.wv.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of WV";
"algs.info.wv.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.wv.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.wv.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.wv.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.wv.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.wv.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.wv.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.wv.overview.p1" = "**WV**, short for **Winter Variation**, solves the final F2L pair while also orienting the last layer in cases where the last-layer edges are already oriented. In practice, it is one of the most approachable gateways into advanced last-slot theory.";
"algs.info.wv.history.p1" = "Winter Variation was published by **Lucas Winter** in 2005 and quickly became one of the best-known advanced last-slot subsets. It is now widely treated as a first step from ordinary F2L into larger systems such as **VLS** and **ZBLS**.";
"algs.info.wv.size.b1" = "Commonly counted as **27 algorithms**";
"algs.info.wv.size.b2" = "Applies when the final pair is available and **last-layer edges are already oriented**";
"algs.info.wv.size.b3" = "Skips plain OLL by finishing the slot and orienting the last layer together";
"algs.info.wv.size.b4" = "Often learned before larger last-slot families because the set is compact and practical";
"algs.info.wv.insights.p1" = "WV is appealing because it offers a clear efficiency gain without demanding a huge algorithm commitment. For many CFOP solvers, it is the first advanced subset that feels both learnable and immediately useful.";
"algs.info.wv.insights.p2" = "The set also teaches an important conceptual shift: the last slot is not only something to finish cleanly, but also an opportunity to shape the last layer before it even begins.";
"algs.info.wv.insights.p3" = "Because of its size and practical payoff, WV often acts as a gateway. Solvers who enjoy it frequently go on to explore **VLS**, **ZBLS**, or other edge-orientation-aware last-slot systems.";
"algs.info.wv.recognition.p1" = "WV is recognized by looking at the final pair and confirming that the last-layer edges are already oriented. From there, the pair structure and insertion direction determine the exact case.";
"algs.info.wv.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for cubers with stable F2L who want their first serious last-slot subset. It is especially good for CFOP solvers who already notice edge orientation during solves and want more efficient transitions into the last layer.";
"algs.info.wv.quote.p1" = "“Winter Variation is often the first moment a solver realizes the last slot can do more than finish F2L — it can also quietly simplify the entire last layer.”";
"algs.info.sv.title" = "About SV";
"algs.info.sv.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of SV";
"algs.info.sv.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.sv.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.sv.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.sv.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.sv.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.sv.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.sv.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.sv.overview.p1" = "**SV**, commonly called **Summer Variation**, is a smaller advanced last-slot family related to WV-style ideas. It focuses on selected final-slot cases where a specialized insertion gives a cleaner or more efficient transition into the last layer.";
"algs.info.sv.history.p1" = "Unlike WV, SV is less known as a single historical milestone and more as a community label for a focused branch of advanced last-slot techniques. It developed naturally as cubers kept extending the logic behind efficient final-slot inserts.";
"algs.info.sv.size.b1" = "Usually treated as a **focused subset**, not a giant standalone system";
"algs.info.sv.size.b2" = "Smaller and more selective than broad families like **VLS**";
"algs.info.sv.size.b3" = "Most useful when a solver already recognizes final-slot structure comfortably";
"algs.info.sv.size.b4" = "Often learned case by case rather than as a formal all-at-once project";
"algs.info.sv.insights.p1" = "SV is best understood as a practical extension of advanced last-slot thinking rather than a universal milestone set. Its value comes from picking off cases where the payoff is obvious and the recognition burden stays manageable.";
"algs.info.sv.insights.p2" = "Because the label is used a bit more loosely than sets like PLL or OLL, solvers often encounter SV through curated case collections instead of a single canonical learning path.";
"algs.info.sv.insights.p3" = "That flexibility can actually be a strength: if a few cases fit naturally into your solves, SV can improve endings without demanding that you commit to a very large body of algorithms.";
"algs.info.sv.recognition.p1" = "SV recognition depends on the same broad ingredients as other last-slot subsets: the final pair structure, available insertion direction, and the last-layer state you want to preserve or improve.";
"algs.info.sv.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced solvers who already enjoy WV, VLS, or ZBLS-style thinking and want a few more efficient final-slot options without jumping straight into another huge family.";
"algs.info.sv.quote.p1" = "“Summer Variation is less about memorizing a famous fixed set and more about collecting the final-slot cases that are simply too efficient to ignore.”";
"algs.info.zbls.title" = "About ZBLS";
"algs.info.zbls.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of ZBLS";
"algs.info.zbls.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.zbls.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.zbls.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.zbls.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.zbls.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.zbls.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.zbls.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.zbls.overview.p1" = "**ZBLS**, short for **ZB Last Slot**, solves the final F2L pair while also orienting the last-layer edges. It is one of the key bridges between ordinary CFOP F2L and the broader **ZB** family of last-layer efficiency systems.";
"algs.info.zbls.history.p1" = "ZBLS grew out of the larger **ZB method** developed by **Zbigniew Zborowski** and **Ron van Bruchem**. As the method evolved, speedcubers organized the final-slot portion into its own learnable family, since it offered practical efficiency even without learning all of ZBLL.";
"algs.info.zbls.size.b1" = "A **large last-slot family**, far bigger than compact sets like WV";
"algs.info.zbls.size.b2" = "Built around solving the last slot while leaving **EO complete** for the last layer";
"algs.info.zbls.size.b3" = "Acts as a foundation for endings that continue into **ZBLL** or other one-look finishes";
"algs.info.zbls.size.b4" = "Usually learned selectively because the full family is too large for most cubers to tackle at once";
"algs.info.zbls.insights.p1" = "ZBLS matters because it changes the role of the last slot. Instead of merely finishing F2L, the final insertion becomes a chance to set up a much stronger last-layer state before recognition even starts.";
"algs.info.zbls.insights.p2" = "In practical terms, many solvers do not approach ZBLS as one massive project. They learn the most ergonomic or frequent cases first, especially those that connect naturally with WV- or VLS-style recognition.";
"algs.info.zbls.insights.p3" = "For theory-minded cubers, ZBLS is also one of the clearest windows into how advanced methods connect: F2L structure, edge orientation, and last-layer planning all meet in one place.";
"algs.info.zbls.recognition.p1" = "ZBLS is recognized by reading the final pair together with the desired edge-orientation outcome. The exact case depends on how the pair is arranged and what insertion preserves or creates the edge state you want.";
"algs.info.zbls.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced CFOP solvers with strong F2L and a serious interest in last-slot systems. It is especially relevant for cubers who already enjoy WV or want to understand the practical side of the broader ZB method.";
"algs.info.zbls.quote.p1" = "“ZBLS is where the last slot stops being a cleanup task and starts becoming a full strategic setup for the last layer.”";
"algs.info.1lll.title" = "About 1LLL";
"algs.info.1lll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of 1LLL";
"algs.info.1lll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.1lll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.1lll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.1lll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.1lll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.1lll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.1lll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.1lll.overview.p1" = "**1LLL**, short for **One-Look Last Layer**, is not one single fixed set but an umbrella idea: solving the entire last layer in one algorithm from many different prepared states. Families like **ZBLL** are among its most famous structured examples.";
"algs.info.1lll.history.p1" = "The phrase 1LLL became a convenient community shorthand as speedcubers organized increasingly efficient last-layer systems. Rather than naming one historical method, it describes the broader goal of collapsing the last layer into a single recognized finish.";
"algs.info.1lll.size.b1" = "There is **no single fixed algorithm count**, because 1LLL is an umbrella over multiple families";
"algs.info.1lll.size.b2" = "Well-known subsets under the 1LLL idea include **ZBLL** and other edge-conditioned one-look systems";
"algs.info.1lll.size.b3" = "The total space is extremely large, so most cubers only learn selected families";
"algs.info.1lll.size.b4" = "Its efficiency ceiling is extremely high, but the learning burden is also among the heaviest in speedcubing";
"algs.info.1lll.insights.p1" = "1LLL is best treated as a concept, not a normal milestone set. It represents the idea of a fully compressed last layer, but in practice it breaks down into many smaller systems, each with its own recognition and prerequisites.";
"algs.info.1lll.insights.p2" = "That is why almost nobody learns “full 1LLL” in the literal sense. Instead, solvers pick structured subsets that fit their method, recognition habits, and appetite for memorization.";
"algs.info.1lll.insights.p3" = "Even so, thinking in 1LLL terms can be useful. It helps explain why sets like COLL, OLLCP, and ZBLL feel related: they all move toward the same goal of shrinking the last layer into fewer and fewer meaningful decisions.";
"algs.info.1lll.recognition.p1" = "Recognition in 1LLL depends entirely on the subset being used. Some families start from oriented edges, some from last-slot conditions, and some from broader OLL-style patterns plus extra permutation detail.";
"algs.info.1lll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for theory-minded advanced solvers who already understand the main last-layer families and want to see how those systems fit into a larger one-look framework, rather than for anyone looking for a small practical next set.";
"algs.info.1lll.quote.p1" = "“1LLL is less a set you finish learning and more a horizon that explains why so many advanced last-layer systems keep pushing toward the same idea: solve everything at once.”";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.title" = "About Advanced F2L";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of Advanced F2L";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.overview.p1" = "**Advanced F2L** refers to the more structured side of F2L beyond basic intuitive pairing. It usually focuses on awkward pair states, higher-efficiency inserts, and last-slot cases where a more formal algorithm can preserve flow or reduce move count.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.history.p1" = "As CFOP matured, cubers gradually cataloged the awkward F2L cases that were worth solving with fixed algorithms instead of pure intuition. Over time, these collections became a practical middle ground between intuitive F2L and large last-slot systems.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.size.b1" = "Often organized as a **case collection**, not one rigid universal set";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.size.b2" = "Usually focuses on awkward inserts, special pair states, and efficient last-slot situations";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.size.b3" = "The goal is not just fewer moves, but also better **lookahead** and cleaner turning";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.size.b4" = "Acts as a bridge between intuitive F2L and subsets like **WV**, **VLS**, or **CLS**";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.insights.p1" = "Advanced F2L matters because not every pair is worth solving purely on the fly. Some cases are awkward enough that a stable algorithm saves both moves and thinking time.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.insights.p2" = "Unlike full last-layer sets, Advanced F2L is usually learned opportunistically. Solvers add cases one by one as they notice which patterns repeatedly interrupt their flow.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.insights.p3" = "This makes the set especially practical: it strengthens normal solves immediately while also preparing the pattern awareness needed for more formal last-slot systems.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.recognition.p1" = "Recognition in Advanced F2L means reading the corner, edge, and open-slot relationship quickly enough to decide whether the case is best solved intuitively or with a known high-efficiency insert.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for cubers who already have stable intuitive F2L and want to remove repeated bottlenecks before committing to much larger advanced systems.";
"algs.info.advancedf2l.quote.p1" = "“Advanced F2L is where intuition stops being vague and starts becoming structured: you still understand the slot, but you also know exactly which awkward cases deserve a better answer.”";
"algs.info.cls.title" = "About CLS";
"algs.info.cls.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of CLS";
"algs.info.cls.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.cls.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.cls.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.cls.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.cls.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.cls.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.cls.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.cls.overview.p1" = "**CLS**, short for **Corners of the Last Slot**, solves the final F2L pair while also resolving the last-layer corners. It is a more ambitious last-slot family than WV, because the payoff is not only orientation control but a much stronger reduction of the remaining last layer.";
"algs.info.cls.history.p1" = "CLS emerged from the broader effort to push more work into the final slot. As cubers explored how last-slot inserts could influence corners as well as orientation, CLS became one of the recognizable branches in that advanced family tree.";
"algs.info.cls.size.b1" = "A **large last-slot family**, bigger than compact gateway sets like WV";
"algs.info.cls.size.b2" = "Built around solving the final pair while also resolving last-layer corner structure";
"algs.info.cls.size.b3" = "Can lead directly into reduced last-layer finishes with much less remaining work";
"algs.info.cls.size.b4" = "Usually learned selectively rather than as a single all-at-once project";
"algs.info.cls.insights.p1" = "CLS is attractive because it pushes the last slot beyond setup and into real last-layer solving. That makes it conceptually powerful, even if the full learning load is too large for most solvers.";
"algs.info.cls.insights.p2" = "In practice, many solvers treat CLS as a family of high-value cases rather than a full memorization target. The best cases are the ones whose recognition and ergonomics stay manageable in real solves.";
"algs.info.cls.insights.p3" = "Studying CLS also helps build a more connected view of cubing theory: slot structure, corner control, and last-layer compression all become part of one continuous decision.";
"algs.info.cls.recognition.p1" = "CLS recognition depends on reading the final pair together with the corner state you want to preserve or solve. Compared with WV-style sets, the recognition burden is higher because more corner information matters.";
"algs.info.cls.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced CFOP solvers who already enjoy last-slot systems and want to explore cases that do significantly more work than ordinary inserts or simple OLL-skipping subsets.";
"algs.info.cls.quote.p1" = "“CLS is a reminder that the last slot is not just the end of F2L; in the right case, it is already the beginning of the finish.”";
"algs.info.sbls.title" = "About SBLS";
"algs.info.sbls.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of SBLS";
"algs.info.sbls.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.sbls.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.sbls.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.sbls.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.sbls.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.sbls.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.sbls.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.sbls.overview.p1" = "**SBLS**, commonly expanded as **Second Block Last Slot**, is a Roux-oriented family that handles the final piece relationship of the second block in a more algorithmic way. It belongs to the same general idea as advanced last-slot work in CFOP: use the final insertion to improve what comes next.";
"algs.info.sbls.history.p1" = "As Roux users refined second-block efficiency, certain recurring final-slot patterns proved worth cataloging. SBLS grew out of that practical pressure to make the end of second block cleaner and more consistent before CMLL and LSE.";
"algs.info.sbls.size.b1" = "Usually treated as a **focused advanced subset**, not a universal baseline requirement for Roux";
"algs.info.sbls.size.b2" = "Targets the end of second block, where a clean finish can improve the rest of the solve";
"algs.info.sbls.size.b3" = "Its value depends heavily on whether recognition stays fast enough in live solves";
"algs.info.sbls.size.b4" = "Often learned selectively, case by case, by Roux solvers who enjoy extra structure";
"algs.info.sbls.insights.p1" = "SBLS is to Roux what many last-slot families are to CFOP: a way to make the final building step do more than merely finish the block.";
"algs.info.sbls.insights.p2" = "Because Roux already relies heavily on blockbuilding intuition, SBLS is rarely a first priority. It becomes attractive later, when a solver wants a few more efficient endings without abandoning the method's natural flow.";
"algs.info.sbls.insights.p3" = "That makes SBLS especially valuable to theory-minded Roux users who enjoy targeted optimizations rather than giant mandatory sets.";
"algs.info.sbls.recognition.p1" = "SBLS recognition is based on the final second-block relationship and the specific insertion or resolution path that best preserves the shape you want for the next phase.";
"algs.info.sbls.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for established Roux solvers who already understand second-block structure well and want a selective advanced subset rather than a broad method overhaul.";
"algs.info.sbls.quote.p1" = "“SBLS is most useful when second block stops feeling like a construction task and starts feeling like a chance to engineer a better finish.”";
"algs.info.cmll.title" = "About CMLL";
"algs.info.cmll.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of CMLL";
"algs.info.cmll.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.cmll.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.cmll.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.cmll.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.cmll.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.cmll.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.cmll.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.cmll.overview.p1" = "**CMLL**, short for **Corners of the Last Layer**, is a core Roux stage that solves all last-layer corners in one algorithm after the first two blocks are complete. Once CMLL is done, the cube is reduced to the final edge phase of the method.";
"algs.info.cmll.history.p1" = "CMLL developed as a central part of the **Roux method** and is one of the most distinctive algorithm sets associated with that approach. Its structure is closely related to corner-focused families like COLL, but it sits inside Roux's very different solve flow.";
"algs.info.cmll.size.b1" = "Commonly counted as **42 algorithms** in the full set";
"algs.info.cmll.size.b2" = "Leaves only the final edge-solving phase after completion";
"algs.info.cmll.size.b3" = "Recognition is heavily shape-based and often feels compact once the families are learned";
"algs.info.cmll.size.b4" = "One of the most important formal algorithm milestones in Roux";
"algs.info.cmll.insights.p1" = "CMLL is practical because it gives Roux a clean and repeatable one-step corner finish without forcing the method into a CFOP-like last-layer structure.";
"algs.info.cmll.insights.p2" = "Many solvers find that CMLL becomes more manageable once they recognize its strong family patterns. The set is large, but the cases do not feel equally independent once those families are understood.";
"algs.info.cmll.insights.p3" = "It also shows why Roux can remain efficient with relatively little last-layer sprawl: solve the corners cleanly, then let the final edge phase do the rest.";
"algs.info.cmll.recognition.p1" = "CMLL is recognized by the corner pattern of the last layer after the two Roux blocks are built. In practice, many solvers use top-face corner shapes plus a small amount of side information to lock the case quickly.";
"algs.info.cmll.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for any serious Roux solver. Compared with many optional advanced subsets, CMLL is much closer to a core method milestone than a niche side project.";
"algs.info.cmll.quote.p1" = "“CMLL feels powerful because it gives Roux a very disciplined middle ending: corners are finished decisively, and the method can flow straight into its final edge work.”";
"algs.info.4a.title" = "About 4a";
"algs.info.4a.subtitle" = "Definition, History, and Efficiency of 4a";
"algs.info.4a.section.overview" = "Overview";
"algs.info.4a.section.history" = "History";
"algs.info.4a.section.size" = "Size & Efficiency";
"algs.info.4a.section.insights" = "Insights";
"algs.info.4a.section.recognition" = "Recognition";
"algs.info.4a.section.recommended" = "Recommended For";
"algs.info.4a.section.quote" = "Quote";
"algs.info.4a.overview.p1" = "**4a** is commonly used as a shorthand label for a small **edge-orientation** subset. Its role is not to solve a huge standalone stage, but to clean up a very specific edge state so later recognition or finish steps become more efficient.";
"algs.info.4a.history.p1" = "Like many niche shorthand labels in speedcubing, 4a spread through community use more than through one famous formal publication. It survives because the cases are compact and the payoff is easy to explain to solvers already interested in orientation-aware methods.";
"algs.info.4a.size.b1" = "A **small specialized subset**, not a major standalone algorithm family";
"algs.info.4a.size.b2" = "Focused on edge-orientation outcomes rather than broad last-layer coverage";
"algs.info.4a.size.b3" = "Most useful when paired with a method or subset that benefits from controlled edge states";
"algs.info.4a.size.b4" = "Better viewed as a targeted optimization than a general learning milestone";
"algs.info.4a.insights.p1" = "4a is the kind of subset that matters more to specialists than to the average solver. Its cases are small enough to learn, but only worth it if they fit a broader method or planning style you already use.";
"algs.info.4a.insights.p2" = "That makes it a good example of a modern cubing pattern: once the mainstream milestones are learned, many later gains come from small, method-specific subsets rather than giant universal systems.";
"algs.info.4a.insights.p3" = "For solvers who care about edge orientation deeply, even a small set like this can sharpen how they see the cube and connect intermediate phases more cleanly.";
"algs.info.4a.recognition.p1" = "Recognition in 4a is centered on the relevant edge-orientation pattern and whether the case matches the exact state the subset is designed to control.";
"algs.info.4a.recommended.p1" = "Recommended for advanced solvers who already use edge-orientation-aware approaches and want a small, highly specific subset rather than a broad new family.";
"algs.info.4a.quote.p1" = "“A set like 4a is useful not because it is huge, but because it turns one very specific edge state into something predictable and reusable.”";
